title: For Sale:  Charles Lancaster Boxlock 12 GA
postcontent: Charles Lancaster O-grade boxlock 12 gauge self-opening ejector shotgun. Built in 1889 according to factory letter.  28" sleeved barrels choked IC and light modified (by gauge), 2.5" chambers.  Sleeving done by E.C. Ashthorpe of Severn Stoke, Worcester, and the seam is nearly invisible.  Approximate dimensions: 14" LOP to front trigger, 1.5" DAC, 2" DAH, ~3/16" cast off.  6lb. 7oz and very well balanced.  Features Lancaster's distinctive vine-leaf engraving.  Very good condition but does show a bit of bluing wear on the floor plate and muzzle.  Includes Jeff's Outfitters canvas and leather case with accessories and reproduction trade label.  I also have a flat of assorted 2.5 inch shells which I can include at extra cost.    While not as well known in America, Lancaster made guns of similar quality to Holland & Holland, Purdey, and Boss.  Annie Oakley owned four Lancasters.  The O-grade is a unique boxlock built on Frederick Beesley's patent self-opening mechanism, similar to Purdey's self opening sidelock which was also invented by Beesley.  Most London gunmakers outsourced production of their boxlocks to the bigger Birmingham firms; it has been suggested that Lancaster's O-grade was so named because it was built by Charles Osborne.  Many more photos available on request.

title: For Sale:  Izhmash Saiga AK47 converted
postcontent: I purchased this Saiga rifle new-in-box at a gunshow in 2002 when they were still cheap.  It has a 20" barrel which was very hard to find in 7.62x39; in fact, it was the only one at that very large gun show, and I havent seen one since.  I have the original sales receipt.In 2008, I paid Elk River Tool & Die in Houston over $600 to convert the rifle to accept standard AK mags.  They installed a new US made 5 piece fire cotnrol group, a US made flash brake (threaded barrel 14 lefthand), and put a nice Parkerize finish on it.  I have the reciept for the work showing the breakout of everything they did.  It had never fired it prior to the conversion, and I only put one 30 round mag through it after the conversion just to make sure it ran right, and it did. My intention was to make use of the long barrel and create some kind of "mini Druganov".  It has the factory-pinned standard AK scope rail on the L side, and I'm sure it will drive tacks with a decent scope.  I added a Druganov style stock that really makes a great cheek weld and adds a little length over the standard AK military stock.  The overall length is just under 42", making it 4-5" longer than a standard AK.  I like the original forearm from the Saiga...its light, rock-solid, and is on the slim side of aftermarket options available.  Somewhere along the way I lost interest in putting more effort into this rifle and now I'm selling it.  $1100 cash is the firm price...I can wait as long as necessary, or even keep it until the next assault rifle rush.  I will consider shipping the rifle to a FFL of your choosing, but only if you pay me first...I dont know who in the world would do that, but I'm willing if you are.  So I'm sure this will have to be a local deal in the Houston area.  I am flexible and am willing to meet at a gun shop or other public location around lunch time on weekdays, or any weekends.  I will need you to show me a valid Texas driver's license or CCL and sign a release for my records; I will give you a reciept.Thanks

title: For Sale:  Kel Tec RFB, 18", 7.62 NATO
postcontent: RFB stands for Rifle, Forward-ejecting Bullpup. Why forward-ejecting? Because it allows the RFB to be the first truly ambidextrous 7.62 NATO Bullpup ever developed. Upon firing, the patented, dual-extractor system pulls the fired case from the chamber and lifts them to push them into an ejection chute above the barrel, where they exit. The Bullpup configuration and tilting-block mechanism allow the 18" model to be only 26.1" long, or as much as 14" shorter in overall length than its competitors with equal barrel lengths. Furthermore, the stock and mechanism cross-section is similar to a conventional rifle, in stark contrast to existing Bullpup rifles. The RFB is also one of the safest Bullpup ever developed because the breech is separated from the shooters face by two layers of 1.6 mm steel. In the highly unlikely event of a case rupture, gas expansion is directed downwards through the magazine well to protect the shooters head and face.   The RFB is a short-stroke gas piston operated semi-automatic rifle in 7.62 mm NATO caliber. It accepts standard metric FAL type magazines which work "drop free" and do not need to be tilted in. One 20 round magazine is included. Barrels on current models are 18" long; a longer barrel length of 24" available as the hunter variant.. The muzzle is threaded 5/8x24 TPI and comes equipped with our A2-style flash hider.  All controls are fully ambidextrous; the reciprocating operating handle can be switched to either side. The safety disconnects the trigger and blocks the hammer action. A Mil-Spec Picatinny rail is attached rigidly to the barrel assembly. No open sights are provided, allowing the user to select from optics and sight systems available on the market. The RFB comes with a two point sling that can be easily configured to suit the user's preference. Available accessories include a free-floating, four-sided Picatinny forend, bipod mounts, a removable bayonet lug for use with NATO style bayonets including our own Folding Bayonet, and many more.Sorry, not interested in trades.  All FFL rules and regs apply.  FREE SHIPPING!Buy this rifle online at www.copsgunshop.net.
